<br>
Chaining pets allows you to trade time for mana, i.e. taking longer to kill a foe, but using less mana to do so.  Buying time, and hence, mana.  It can be a useful soloing technique, or for crowd control in a group <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(chaining a pet to off-tank one or two adds)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
It also lets you deal with more powerful opponents than you could otherwise.  Sustaining pets can be expensive manawise, and makes the mana bar a hard limit to the toughness of the foes you can handle.  By chaining instead, mana becomes less important.<br>
<br>
For example, I found it took anywhere from six to eight <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Greater Vocaration: Earth</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets to kill an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Elder Wyvern</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>SkyFire</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  There is no way I could win that fight with the traditional <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;sustain and nuke&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> tactic.  While the fight took a while, it also used very little mana, so I did not have to med between fights.  By chaining, I could alternate fighting and pulling, with hardly any downtime.<br>
<br>
At the very least, you should learn to chain pets in order to deal with emergencies, especially crowd control.  There will not always be an enchanter available, or they can die.  The ability to stave off death by chaining pets will serve you well in groups, and impress others with the power that is mage.<br>
<br>
At 30ish though, it may not be a viable technique, at least for soloing.  I would spend at least some effort mastering it anyway, because as I said, it will come in handy.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
